The k command is used to set arbitrary marks in a file, so that
a reference may be made to the marks later.  This may relieve the
user from the need to remember specific block numbers while editing.
You may set up to 26 marks, one for each letter of the alphabet.
Enter a k, and without spacing, enter a lower case letter, and press
enter.  Your location in the file is then marked with that letter.
You may use a reference to that mark whenever you give a block address
to an edway command.  To reference the mark, you use an apostrophe,
often called a tick, followed by the letter that you used for the mark.
It is not actually a block that is marked, but a single millisecond long
atom of sound in the middle of the block.  Marks are thus preserved when
block size is modified with the ms command or the nb command.

